A, B, female from Aana Mudi Shola National Park, India (WAM T109510). A, dorsal view; B, ventral view. C–F, female from Nilgiris, Tamil Nadu, India (ZMUC 12902). C, dorsal view; D, ventral view; E, epigyne, ventral view; F, epigyne, dorsal view). Scale bar = 2.0 mm in A- D; 0.5 mm in E; 0.2 mm in F.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="56.[144,759,198,1290]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
The MNHN apparently does not hold the type material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[280,409,504,525]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis box="[280,409,504,525]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">A. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(C. Rollard, pers. comm.) and we consider it here lost. However, we accept Sherriffs’ (1918, 1919) concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[412,541,565,587]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis box="[412,541,565,587]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">A. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species occurring in southern Indian mountain regions and redescribe the species here based on an examination of Sherriffs’ (1918, 1919) original material (ZMUC12902) and conspecific material from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[144,205,718,740]" name="India" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">India</collectingCountry>
collected more recently by the senior author. In accordance with ICZN Article 75.3.1, we here designate a 
<typeStatus box="[238,327,780,801]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">neotype</typeStatus>
for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[388,517,780,801]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis box="[388,517,780,801]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">A. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to clarify the type locality of the species, which is doubtful based on the original description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Simon E" box="[412,616,840,862]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" refId="ref37714" refString="Simon E. 1895. Histoire naturelle des araignees. Paris: Roret." type="book" year="1895">Simon (1895: 805</bibRefCitation>
: ‘montagnes de l’Inde’). This designation is also necessary to explicitly avoid confusion with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Tikader" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[531,722,902,923]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="himalayaensis">
<emphasis box="[531,722,902,923]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">P. himalayaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a congeneric species that is found in northern mountainous regions of 
<collectingCountry box="[361,425,963,985]" name="India" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[144,759,198,1290]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
We here propose the transfer of this species to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" box="[144,204,1024,1045]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[144,204,1024,1045]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Plebs</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Simon, 1895)" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[220,513,1024,1046]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[220,344,1025,1046]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">P. mitratus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Simon E" box="[361,505,1024,1046]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" refId="ref37714" refString="Simon E. 1895. Histoire naturelle des araignees. Paris: Roret." type="book" year="1895">Simon, 1895</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[522,644,1024,1046]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, based on somatic and genitalic morphology, in particular the distinct ventral coloration of the abdomen with inverted light U-shaped pattern and additional spots anterolateral of the spinnerets (
<figureCitation box="[514,646,1146,1168]" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="55.[164,243,1584,1603]" captionTargetBox="[327,1275,195,1553]" captionTargetId="figure-95@55.[323,1283,195,1554]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="Figure 34. Plebs mitratus comb. nov. A, B, female from Aana Mudi Shola National Park, India (WAM T109510). A, dorsal view; B, ventral view. C–F, female from Nilgiris, Tamil Nadu, India (ZMUC 12902). C, dorsal view; D, ventral view; E, epigyne, ventral view; F, epigyne, dorsal view). Scale bar = 2.0 mm in A-D; 0.5 mm in E; 0.2 mm in F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408791/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Fig. 34B, D</figureCitation>
) (synapomorphy of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" box="[266,326,1177,1198]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[266,326,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Plebs</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<figureCitation box="[341,407,1177,1199]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="12.[144,223,1760,1779]" captionTargetBox="[250,1316,199,1728]" captionTargetId="graphics-0@12.[250,1316,206,1728]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic hypothesis for Plebs within a taxon sampling of Australian ‘eriophorine’ orb-weaving spiders (Araneidae) (length = 114, consistency index = 0.38, retention index = 0.72). Full circles indicate unambiguous synapomorphies and open circles homoplasious character state changes. Character numbers (above circles) and states (below circles) as in Table 1. The topology only shows unambiguous character state changes. Bremer support values are given in circles below branches." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408731/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). In contrast to all other Asian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" box="[144,204,1208,1229]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[144,204,1208,1229]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Plebs</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the species is redescribed here in detail as no illustrations or detailed descriptions are available for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[144,269,1269,1290]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis box="[144,269,1269,1290]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">P. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[144,483,1343,1365]" box="[144,483,1343,1365]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis box="[144,289,1343,1364]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Distribution:</emphasis>
Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[415,479,1343,1365]" name="India" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[144,759,1418,1685]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis box="[144,562,1418,1439]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Life history and habitat preferences:</emphasis>
Although adults have been observed throughout the year, the peak occurrence is from September to January. The spiders prefer a temperate climate and are generally restricted to higher altitudes (above 
<quantity box="[587,674,1540,1562]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
). Webs can generally be found in low grassy vegetation in open pockets of forests especially on the edges of forest trails. Webs are often decorated with stabilimentum (M. M. Joseph, pers. observ.).
</paragraph>
